      • getNearestRightEntryLink

        public static Link getNearestRightEntryLink(Network network,
                                            Coord coord)
        Finds the (approx.) nearest link to a given point on the map, such that the point lies on the right side of the directed link, if such a link exists. It searches first for the nearest node, and then for the nearest link originating or ending at that node and fulfilling the above constraint.

        Special cases: nodes:o ; links:<-- ; coord:x No right entry link exists 

         
 o<-1--o returning
 | . . ^ nearest left
 |2 . 4| entry link
 v .x. | (link.id=3)
 o--3->o<br>
        No right entry link exists but more than one nearest left entry link exist 
         
 o<-1--o returning
 | . . ^ nearest left
 |2 x 4| entry link with the
 v . . | lowest link id
 o--3->o (link.id=1)
        More than one nearest right entry link exist 
         
 o--1->o returning
 ^ . . | nearest right
 |2 x 4| entry link with the
 | . . v lowest link id
 o<-3--o (link.id=1)

 o<----7&8--x->o (link.id=7)
        Parameters:
        coord - the coordinate for which the closest link should be found
        Returns:
        the link found closest to coord and oriented such that the point lies on the right of the link.

      • getNearestLink

        public static Link getNearestLink(Network network,
                                  Coord coord)
        Finds the (approx.) nearest link to a given point on the map. It searches first for the nearest node, and then for the nearest link originating or ending at that node.
        Parameters:
        coord - the coordinate for which the closest link should be found
        Returns:
        the link found closest to coord
        See Also:
        NetworkUtils#getNearestLinkExactly(Network, Coord)}

      • getLeftmostTurnExcludingU

        public static Link getLeftmostTurnExcludingU(Link inLink)
        Calculates the most 'left' outLink for a given inLink (oriented from north to south). That's the link a driver would refer to when turning left (no u-turn), even if there is only one link going to the right.
        Parameters:
        inLink - The inLink given
        Returns:
        outLink, or null if there is only one outLink back to the inLink's fromNode.

      • getOutLinksSortedClockwiseByAngle

        public static TreeMap<Double,Link> getOutLinksSortedClockwiseByAngle(Link inLink)
        Calculates the orientation of outgoing links for a given incoming link beginning from the right if the inLink goes north to south. The most 'left' outLink comes last. The link back to the inLink's upstream Node is ignored.

        Comments/questions:
        • What does the "north to south" part mean? Can't we just sort outLinks right to left no matter where we come from? kai, aug'16
        • In fact, a test (NetworkUtilsTest.getOutLinksSortedByAngleTest()) does not confirm the javadoc. The "north to south" is irrelevant. But instead, it sorts links left to right instead of right to left.
        If someone can confirm this, please comment out all these remarks. kai, aug'16

        Parameters:
        inLink - The inLink given
        Returns:
        Collection of outLinks, or an empty collection if there are only outLinks back to the inLink's fromNode.
